title.rendered: Carlos Alcaraz’s Roger Federer impersonation at the French Open in awe of Novak Djokovic

content.rendered:
Novak Djokovic made the most of his experience to outclass world no.1 Carlos Alcaraz Garfia in the first semi-final of the ongoing French Open. The two-time French Open champion, who is chasing a record 23rd men’s Grand Slam title and third Roland Garros crown, defeated an ailing Alcaraz 6-2, 5-7, 6-1, 6-1 to become the oldest men’s finalist in Paris since Bill Tilden in 1930. After making it a set apiece, Alcaraz barely moved in the third and fourth sets due to his physical struggles. This allowed Djokovic to beat him on Court Philippe Chatrier.

During the second set, Alcaraz hit the shot of the tournament. This left everyone inside the arena, including Djokovic in complete awe.

(Read Also: I don’t think drama-free Grand Slam can happen for me: Djokovic)

The 36-year-old tempted Alcaraz with a drop shot, which the 20-year-old returned. Djokovic played a deep shot which led Alcaraz to scramble to the baseline.

While everyone thought the 20-year-old would try to loft the ball over Djokovic, he did the unthinkable by sending the ball toward his opponent’s right with a delicate flick.

The crowd was in complete awe and stood up to applaud the youngster while Djokovic and Alcaraz laughed.

Dos punts identics amb 17 anys de diferencia. Semifinal de Roland Garros 2023 Djokovic-Alcaraz. Semifinal de Roland Garros 2006 Federer-Nalbandian pic.twitter.com/Qvsj1XcVsa

— Joan R Vallvé (@joanRvallve) June 9, 2023

After the match, Djokovic backed Alcaraz to win the French Open “multiple times” after the young Spaniard suffered severe cramps that derailed his title hopes on Friday.

“It was very demanding physically for both of us, and things like that physically, cramps or whatever he was struggling with, can happen,” said Djokovic, who will meet last year’s runner-up Casper Ruud in his 34th Grand Slam final.

“Respect for him for hanging in there until the very end, really. It was obvious that he struggled with his movement.
